=================
Short Description
=================

    ESP is a very fast archiver. It has got a good compression algorithm,
 that is in the most cases better than the one of commonly used archivers.
 It was written in assembly, so it uses very little place on your disk.
 The ESP complete program package contains the following files:

    ESP.EXE      - Compression Program
    UNESP.EXE    - Decompression Program
    ESP2EXE.COM  - Self-Extracting Maker
    ESPLINK.COM  - Convert fragments to a single archive file
    GIF2PIC.COM  - Picture converter for graphics archive-comments
    ANS2BIN.COM  - Simple ANSI to BIN converter for color archive-comments
    MANUAL.*     - Documentation files
    TECHNOTE.TXT - File-formats & ESP lister in Pascal
    TEST.TXT     - This is a test, please read it!
    WHATSNEW.TXT - New features of ESP

==============
Command Syntax
==============

    For now, ESP has got only a few command parameters and switches,
 here they are:

 ESP: the compression program
 ~~~
 Usage: ESP [/switches] arc_name[.ESP] [source_path\][filemask] [@listfile]
 (Square brackets are used to indicate that the parameter is not necessary)

 <Commands>
 None, ESP always compresses.

 <Switches>
 /R       recursively scan subdirs
 /P       without /R: save subdir's name
          with /R: don't save pathnames
 /Mx      select compression method where x means:
                                     0=best 3=fast 4=storing (default=0)
 /J       disable repeat-search mode
 /Sabcd   sorting priority   default=1240 (size, path, attrib, name)
                             a, b, c and d is one of the follows:
                             0 = Name
                             1 = Size
                             2 = Path
                             3 = Date/Time
                             4 = Attribute
 /T          disable internal EXTENSION-table
 /Gpassword  garble with password (encrypt file)
             (if you don't give a password, ESP will prompt for it)
 /Cn=name    use archive comment file 'name' type 'n'
               1 = ASCII TEXT
               2 = Color text  (binary screen format)
               4 = 320x200x256 (old PIC format, works only with RAW2PIC)
               5 = 320x200xN   (new PIC, works with GIF2PIC.COM converter)
               6 = 640x480xN   (new PIC, works with GIF2PIC.COM converter)
 /D[sn[,ss]] add Data Recovery Record to archive
                  sn=number of sectors    (default=4)
                  ss=(size of sector)/256 (default=2)
 /Vnnn[K|M]  enable multiple volumes, volume size is nnn  (example: /V1440K)
 /B          enable BEEPing (if user input is needed or at the end
                             of compression)
 /Y          always Yes option (don't wait for a key before next volume)
 /MM         enable MultiMedia compression method for 8-bit sound and
             256-color/greyscale images.  Do not use for already compressed
             files, for example GIF, JPG, MPG, MP3...
             It works only with BMP, PCX, RAW, SCO, WAV, VOC, MOD, S3M, XM...
 /MM2        enable MultiMedia compression method for 24-bit images
 /MEx        select method (1=old or 2=new) of encryption (default=2)

 *** Note: During the compression process you can press F1 for playing
           TETRIS or F2 for playing NIBBLES.

 UNESP: the decompression program
 ~~~~~
 Usage:
  UNESP command[switch][password] arc_name[.ESP] [dest_dir\] [path\][filemask]
        [@listfile]

 (Square brackets have got the same meaning as above, they are used
  to indicate that the parameter is not necessary)

 <Commands>
  ?       View help message
  e       Extract files from archive
  x       eXtract files with full path
  l       List contents of archive
  v       Verbosely list contents of archive
  t       Test archive

 <Switches>
  f       list to bin file - works with 'L'&'V' command (example: UNESP VF arc bin)
  k       wait for a key at end of every screen
  p       set password   (example: UNESP XPsecret FILE.ESP)
          (if you don't give a password, UNESP will prompt for it)
  s       skip comment(s) & DRR handling
  y       always Yes
  n       always No
  b       enable BEEP

 ESP2EXE: self-extract maker from an ESP archive (Create EXE)
 ~~~~~~~
 Usage: ESP2EXE archive_name.ESP [exe_name.EXE]

 Note: Don't convert a password protected ESP file to EXE and don't use with
       older ESP files, 'cause the decompression routine doesn't handle the
       password and older ESP files.

       There are two routines, a small and a smaller, the program
       automatically selects the better one. The smaller routine doesn't
       handle file comments and DRR.

 ESPLINK: archive converter, makes a single archive from archive fragments
 ~~~~~~~
 Usage: ESPLINK first_fragment[.ESP] [single_arc_file.ESP]

 Note: ESPLINK will wait for a disk-change, if it can't open the next
       fragment.

 GIF2PIC: picture converter for archive-comments
 ~~~~~~~  (GIF format -> ESP's new PIC format)

 Usage: GIF2PIC picture_name[.GIF] [picture_name.PIC]

 Handles 2, 16 and 256 color pictures with any resolution. You can add this
 picture as a comment to an ESP-archive, using the /C5 or /C6 switch.
 (/C5 will show the comment in 320x200, /C6 in 640x480)
 Works only with GIF87-format pictures!!!

 Note: See technical notes for PIC-structure in TECHNOTE.TXT!

 ANS2BIN: simple ANSI to BINary converter for color archive-comments
 ~~~~~~~
 Usage: ANS2BIN [/number_of_lines] picture_name[.ANS] [picture_name.BIN]
 Example: ANS2BIN /20 LOGO.ANS LOGO.BIN
 You can add a BIN file as a comment to your ESP-archive with the command
 /C2:
   ESP /C2=LOGO.BIN archive.ESP

 Note #1: This utility cannot handle animated pictures, or pictures
          larger than one screen!

 Note #2: You must have an ANSI-driver installed (for example ANSI.SYS from
          DOS) before you can run this utility. But an ANSI-driver isn't
          needed to view color archive-comments! If your ANSI-editor
          supports binary (.BIN) file-format, you don't need to use this
          program.

 Note #3: You can use ANSI-files directly with /C1 option, but you need
          to have an ANSI-driver installed for UNESP (or SFX) to show
          your comment.

